@Jtrusz Jared, going with your base rate on this with a slight bit of increase due to uncertainty and possible opportunities with the inside view.   Even though 7 countries dropped since President Tsai was elected in 2016, none of dropped since her re-election in January 2020.  I would presume that the relationships that she has built with the remaining 14 (I'm counting the Holy See as a non-starter for bowing out) will only get stronger as the reduced number of countries is easier to manage.   The remaining countries are smaller countries, with smaller voices in global affairs.  They can relate to Taiwan's situation, and their recognition only increases by staying in the game.  However as @CatherineN stated below, China could offer a really good relief/development package to draw countries such as Haiti, Guatemala, Honduras, or Nicaragua into their fold, but is the juice worth the squeeze? Especially as China watches their dollars more closely with COVID and BRI priorities.  This logic can be applied in the Caribbean as well, most of the countries still listed do fairly well with the tourism industry but that has been impacted by COVID.  Will China make investments to draw them away from Taiwan?  With a COVID vaccine expected to rollout, these countries will likely wait and see what happens there before making any big decision.  Unless countries start dropping China in favor of Taiwan, Im not sure that China will go out of their way to individually lure the remaining countries.   However, the below may have impacts soon:
1) RCEP signing could pull in both Oceania and Latin American countries, doubtful that this will have impacts by the end of February.
2) BRI - based on what I am reading, increased dialogue and activity (BRI or separate trade agreements) are taking place more and more in Latin America each day.
